{"cursor":"5695","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox person\n| name = Samuel S. Brown image = imagesize = caption = birth_date = December 15,\n| 1842 birth_place = Pittsburgh, United States death_date = December 11, 1905\n| death_place = Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, United States death_cause =\n| resting_place = resting_place_coordinates = residence = Squirrel Hill\n| (Pittsburgh) education = occupation = Coal magnate, Racehorse owner/breeder\n| known_for = party = spouse = Lizzie P. Pollock children = W. Harry Brown\n| parents = William Henry Brown relations = boards = National Bank of Commerce\n| (Pittsburgh, Pa.), First Nation Bank (Dawson, Pa.), Ohio Railway Company\n| religion = box_width = 23em\n}} 'Captain Samuel Smith Brown' (December 15, 1842 - December 11, 1905) was an\nAmerican businessman and a prominent Thoroughbred racehorse owner/breeder and\nracetrack owner.\n\nA native of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, Samuel Brown was a student at Washington &\nJefferson College when he left to serve with the Union Army during the American\nCivil War. On February 22, 1861, Brown and Rhodes Stansbury Sutton founded the\nDelta Tau Delta fraternity chapter at Washington & Jefferson College, playing an\ninstrumental role in saving the fraternity from extinction when the first\nBethany College chapter closed on the eve of the Civil War. Brown and Sutton's\nfamous winter ride from Jefferson College at Canonsburg to Bethany, West\nVirginia is still honored in fraternity history, and the result of their choice\nto join the fraternity lives on, as W&J hosts the oldest Delta Tau Delta chapter\nin continuous existence. From a wealthy family, he inherited coal mining\noperations founded by his father. He would grow and expand the business,\noperating six coal mines supported by a fleet of barges and a controlling\ninterest in a railroad for shipping the coal. In addition, Brown owned several\nhotels in various cities around the United States.\n","linknr":137,"